uk.co.strangeskies.reflection.codegen

Class ClassSignature<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • uk.co.strangeskies.reflection.codegen.ClassSignature<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the intersection of the supertypes of the described class
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    AnnotatedSignature<ClassSignature<T>>, ParameterizedSignature<ClassSignature<T>>, Signature<ClassSignature<T>>

    public class ClassSignature<T>
extends Object
implements ParameterizedSignature<ClassSignature<T>>
    Separating the logic for declaring the class into a builder allows us to ensure the type of the class is immutable once an actual ClassDefinition object is instantiated. This means that the type can be safely reasoned about before any class members are defined or any implementation details are specified.

    A class signature contains a number of method signatures. Some of these signatures may be implied by inheritance, and some may be explicitly attached. When a class signature is declared, each of those signatures is realized into a corresponding method declaration.

      • withAnnotations

        public ClassSignature<T> withAnnotations(Collection<? extends Annotation> annotations)
        Description copied from interface: AnnotatedSignature
        Derive a version of this declaration with the given annotations. Users should take care not to specify annotations which could not be applied to the declaration due to their Target, as there is no validation of applicability.

        Annotations already present on the receiving declaration will be replaced rather than appended.

        Specified by:
